subject: phosphor-hwmon: install configs from repo
commitMessage:
phosphor-hwmon: install configs from repo

Use meson to build the package.

This change required as a part of privilege separation work:
  https://github.com/openbmc/openbmc/issues/3383

This change should be merged after individual repo change:
  https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-hwmon/+/40277

Signed-off-by: Anton D. Kachalov <gmouse@google.com>
Change-Id: I542645d55b8646e0ddb3fb95f50a1cd87334706e

Patch Set 3:

How I can run generate_busconfig_acls() being a part of the package repo/meson at the ROOTFS postprocessing? I tho it's impossible.

While the provided dbus config files might come from different packages, we wouldn't know in advance which package should do postinst. Or we have to re-add (duplicate) this part of code in every single package that provides the hwmon configs.

Change has been successfully merged by Brad Bishop

I'd like to see this in-repo as well.  You can use meson options to replace tokens in the resulting file if necessary.  Here is an example (although this one doesn't have tokens...https://github.com/openbmc/openpower-pnor-code-mgmt/blob/master/meson.build#L226

This code doesn't seem, to me, to be related to the commit message.  Adding busconfigs are not critical to the change of having the repo deliver its config, are they?

I'd really like to see this code put into a separate class.  It isn't obvious how it is related to the obmc-phosphor-image and it is a lot of clutter.  I am fine if you have obmc-phosphor-image `include` this new bbclass though.

If we assume that hwmon configs can be only shipped from sensor package (including bbappend recipes), then we can move this into postinstall script in the package recipe.

It related because it produces a correct configuration files for the shipped hwmon env files. The change is not separate because I'm shipping the whole set of configs within the change.

> If we assume that hwmon configs can be only shipped from sensor package (including bbappend recipes), then we can move this into postinstall script in the package recipe.

You'd want to check with someone from IBM on this.  They're the most likely to generate hwmon configs from another recipe, I think.

> It related because it produces a correct configuration files for the shipped hwmon env files. The change is not separate because I'm shipping the whole set of configs within the change.

This hasn't convinced me.  busconfigs are a security feature that you are working on.  They're not related to this commit and can be added separately, right?
Moved it to separate follow-up change that is tightened with introduced "sensor-id" argument.
I think you can get rid of all the bb.utils.contains stuff and just put this.  Bitbake should ignore any FILES it is missing (because they can also be wildcards).
Done
obv we'll want this removed before merge.
For sure.
Whoa.  What is this?  Why do we need to change the libdir?
Otherwise, the service files will be installed under /usr/lib/systemd instead of required /lib/systemd. That is how systemd is being compiled too in poky meta.
This silly but you could remove this file from the commit if you end up updating this.
Yeah, just forget to drop that.
Done
Sorry, this still seems wrong to me.  Let me look at the hwmon commit and see if I can provide suggestions.

https://github.com/openbmc/openbmc/blob/master/poky/meta/recipes-core/systemd/systemd_247.4.bb#L205-L209

Can we rename libdir to rootlibdir in the same fashion?

It seems like we need to specify something like `udevrulesdir` like in systemd/meson.build:

> udevlibexecdir = join_paths(rootprefixdir, 'lib/udev')
> udevrulesdir = join_paths(udevlibexecdir, 'rules.d')
